<!-- ABOUT FIRE HAZARDS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Fire Hazards</h2>
  <p>
    Fires occur when heat, fuel, and oxygen combine ‚Äî known as the ‚ÄúFire Triangle.‚Äù Industrial fires may be
    triggered by chemicals, gases, electrical faults, machinery overheating, or human errors.
  </p>
  <p>
    Understanding fire behavior and types is essential for safe evacuation and extinguishing.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- FIRE CLASSES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Fire Classes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Class A:</strong> Solid materials (wood, paper, cloth).</li>
    <li><strong>Class B:</strong> Flammable liquids (oil, petrol, paints).</li>
    <li><strong>Class C:</strong> Flammable gases (LPG, CNG, methane).</li>
    <li><strong>Class D:</strong> Metals (magnesium, sodium, potassium).</li>
    <li><strong>Class K:</strong> Kitchen oils & grease fires.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- EXTINGUISHER USAGE -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Fire Extinguisher Usage</h2>
  <p>Use the <strong>P.A.S.S.</strong> technique:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>P</strong> ‚Äì Pull the pin.</li>
    <li><strong>A</strong> ‚Äì Aim at the base of fire.</li>
    <li><strong>S</strong> ‚Äì Squeeze the handle.</li>
    <li><strong>S</strong> ‚Äì Sweep side to side.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Water extinguishers should NOT be used on electrical or oil fires.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- ELECTRICAL FIRE HANDLING -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Handling Electrical Fires</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Turn OFF the main electricity supply immediately.</li>
    <li>Use only CO‚ÇÇ or Dry Chemical Powder (DCP) extinguishers.</li>
    <li>Do NOT use water ‚Äî risk of electrocution.</li>
    <li>Move away from live wires and metal bodies.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- INDUSTRIAL & LAB SAFETY -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Industrial & Laboratory Safety</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Wear proper PPE ‚Äî gloves, goggles, masks, lab coats.</li>
    <li>Store chemicals in labeled, sealed containers.</li>
    <li>Do not mix chemicals without guidance.</li>
    <li>Ensure good ventilation in labs/workshops.</li>
    <li>Know emergency shower & eye-wash locations.</li>
    <li>Report strong smells, leaks, or spills immediately.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HELPING OTHERS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>How to Help Others During a Fire</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Guide others to fire exits calmly.</li>
    <li>Help children, elderly, and injured people evacuate.</li>
    <li>Close doors behind you to slow smoke spread.</li>
    <li>Call emergency services ‚Äî do not assume someone else has.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

